## Hints for Future Agents
- The rewrite deliberately uses POSITIVE framing (do X) over negative (NEVER/REJECT) because Opus 4.x follows positive instructions more reliably and all-caps imperatives risk overtriggering. Preserve that if editing.
- It uses XML tags (<role>, <scope>, <steps>, <example>) intentionally for parse separation. Don't strip them.
- It references rules/simple.md by explicit path (NOT a [[simple]] wikilink) because Opus 4.8's literalism would treat a dangling wikilink as a dead pointer.
- The agent flagged a real tradeoff: the five <example> blocks roughly double the file length, and this is always-on context (per-turn token cost). A leaner variant keeping only Steps 1/2/5 examples was offered. User has NOT yet decided; left full version in place. This is an OPEN QUESTION.
- Hard constraint from user: no attribution to Musk or anyone. Keep it that way.

## Codebase Discoveries
- rules/ files either have YAML frontmatter with a 'paths:' key (path-scoped, e.g. gopls-lsp.md scoped to **/*.go) or no frontmatter (global, e.g. simple.md). subtractive-engineering.md is intentionally global.
- Repo uses conventional commit prefixes (feat/chore/docs/refactor with scopes like nvim, rules, settings, abatilo-core).
- Repo commits directly to master (no feature-branch workflow in recent history); user explicitly wanted push to master.

